尽管大部份[[英语圈|英语圈]]的國家都開始避忌食用馬肉，但是在[[20世纪30年代|1930年代]]之前，马肉和[[驴肉|驴肉]]在英國仍然被視作普通肉類食用。這種風氣在[[约克郡|约克郡]]尤其盛行。<ref>''Eating Up Italy: Voyages on a Vespa'' by [[Matthew_Fort|Matthew Fort]]. 2005, p253. ISBN 0-00-721481-2</ref>在[[美国|美国]]战后粮食短缺的时候，马肉亦被廣泛食用，<ref>Charles Grutzner, [http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F10E11FD385C107A93C7AB1782D85F428485F9&scp=4&sq=horse%20meat&st=cse Horse Meat Consumption By New Yorkers Is Rising; Newark Dealer Reports 60% of Customers Are From City--Weinstein Will Not Prohibit Sale of the Flesh Here] 25 Sept 1946</ref>[[医院|医院]]也會烹調馬肉給傷者食用。<ref>James E. Powers, [http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F60B11FB385C107A93CBAB1782D85F428485F9&scp=10&sq=horse%20meat&st=cse NEAR-BY HOSPITALS DOWN TO MINIMUM OF MEAT SUPPLIES], The New York Times, 29 September 1946</ref>隨著馬匹被汽車取代，在美國1920年開始每年有50萬匹馬被製成寵物食物，供[[貓|貓]][[狗|狗]]食用<ref>{{cite book |author1=Paul G. Irwin |title=The state of the animals, 2001 |publisher=Humane Society Press |isbn=978-0-9658942-3-4 |pages=8 |url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/state-of-the-animals-2001/oclc/48528086 |language=en |chapter=Overview: The State of Animals in 2001}}</ref>。

